Description of the City Desk Screen

C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚'s original screen is composed of five different items, each strategically placed for your convenience. These items are: the drag bar, the clipboard, the trashcan, the toolbox and the working page. A snapshot of this screen is shown below.


   SCREEN PICTURE


T‚h‚e‚ ‚D‚r‚a‚g‚ ‚B‚a‚r‚

C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ is mouse and menu driven. All menus are accessed by pointing to the drag bar and holding down  the RIGHT mouse  button.   For a thorough explanation of each of the options in a menu, please see the Reference Guide.
  At the top of the screen you will see a bar that reads "City Desk." By pointing at this drag bar and holding down  the RIGHT mouse button, you will find six separate menus. Each of these menus is described below:

     P‚R‚O‚J‚E‚C‚T‚ -- The function of PROJECT is to handle loading and saving text or graphics on disk, and printing.

     E‚D‚I‚T‚ -- The EDIT menu formats the page and/or text. The EDIT menu also provides a small editor and a special option for inverting or editing graphics.

     P‚R‚E‚F‚E‚R‚E‚N‚C‚E‚S‚ -- The PREFERENCES menu contains many functions that change how C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ works for you.  These functions include options such as loading and saving the default text or page format, choosing the current printer type, and selecting the printer resolution.

     G‚R‚I‚D‚ -- Turning on the grid option is useful for lining up objects on the page. This option forces all objects to be placed at regular intervals.

     T‚O‚O‚L‚B‚O‚X‚ -- Puts the toolbox window on top of or behind all the other windows on the screen.

     F‚L‚O‚W‚ ‚O‚P‚T‚I‚O‚N‚S‚ -- This menu controls the flow and position of the text when a column or page becomes full.


  Located at the right end of the drag bar are the FRONT and BACK gadgets. The FRONT gadget sends the entire C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ screen to the front of all other screens. The BACK is the opposite of the FRONT gadget. The BACK  puts this window behind all others. With these gadgets you can get back to Workbench without leaving C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚. The Workbench screen has the similar gadgets to get you back to the program. Note that pressing the left (A)miga key while at the same time pressing either "M" or "N" will cause your Amiga to toggle between City Desk and WorkBench. (this is similar to the FRONT and BACK gadgets). Also, be aware that some Amiga system error messages (such as INSERT DISK .... IN DRIVE ...) will cause the Workbench screen to come to the front. To get back to City Desk, press the left (A)miga key and the letters M or N.


T‚h‚e‚ ‚C‚l‚i‚p‚b‚o‚a‚r‚d‚

   The clipboard is a place where you can put any object temporarily for use later. This is the background window, behind all the pages.


T‚h‚e‚ ‚T‚r‚a‚s‚h‚c‚a‚n‚

   The trashcan gets rid of any undesirable objects. This trashcan is represented by a skull and crossbones.


T‚h‚e‚ ‚T‚o‚o‚l‚b‚o‚x‚

   The Toolbox provides you everything you need to lay out a page. Some tools have a two-mouse button option. The left mouse button in all cases selects the tool. The right mouse button in some tools calls up the appropriate default options requester. These tools are described in a later section of this manual. Note 
that the toolbox has a drag bar and can be moved around on the screen.

T‚h‚e‚ ‚W‚o‚r‚k‚i‚n‚g‚ ‚P‚a‚g‚e‚

   C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ provides you with a "what you see is what you get"  page window that serves as a guide for placing text or graphics just as if you were cutting and pasting text and figures on an actual sheet of paper.

   Let's follow a clockwise description of this window:
   Located at the top left hand corner is the CLOSE gadget symbol. This item indicates "close the current page." Closing a page does not cause your work to be lost, it simply clears the screen so you can easily open a new page.

   Next to the CLOSE gadget is the window's drag bar or title bar. The current page number is indicated in this bar. To move the window to a different place on the screen, point to the drag bar and hold down the left mouse button. Move the window to the desired location on the screen and release the button.

   At the top right corner you will find two gadgets: the FRONT and BACK gadgets. The FRONT gadget moves this window on top of all other windows on the screen, while the BACK gadget puts this window behind all others. These front and back gadgets only move windows around the C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ screen.

On the right side of the window you will find a slider that positions the screen view up or down on the page. 

At the bottom right hand corner is the RESIZE gadget. This item enlarges or shrinks this page's window.

Located along bottom of the window is another slider which moves the screen view to the left or right on the current page.

Finally in the center of the window is the actual page  originally containing two blank columns. This is your guide for page layout.


Getting Started with Text Files

C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ loads any normal Amiga text file. Text files created from popular word processors such as Scribble!  and editors like EDIT and ED can be imported to C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚.


Difference between Default and Current Formats

There are two methods to alter the text format or the page format. The DEFAULT format sets either the text or page format for all newly created pages or blocks of text. The default format is is set by pointing at either the ABC or the OPEN_PAGE tool in the toolbox and clicking the right mouse button. You may save the default format by selecting the "SAVE..." option under Preferences. For example, if you decide to change the default text format then you click the right mouse button on the ABC tool.
   The CURRENT format sets the style of one particular page or block of text that has already been created. It overrides the default, and may be different for  each page and block of text. The current format is set by selecting the "Edit Text Format" or the "Edit Text Attributes" options from the EDIT menu. If you are changing a page format, the current page options will appear. If you are changing a block of text's attributes, you will have to pick the text to alter by clicking it with your mouse pointer.


Defining the Page Format

By default, C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ gives you a page with two columns of text. The original values for margins, gutter size, and others are given below:
